body:

[Atom Documentation](https://atom.io/docs/api/v1.21.0/)
[Atom Exports](https://github.com/atom/atom/blob/v1.21.0/exports/atom.js)
[Atom Type Definitions](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/tree/master/types/atom)
- [ ] Increase the version number in the header if appropriate.
- [ ] If you are making substantial changes, consider adding a `tslint.json` containing `{ "extends": "dtslint/dt.json" }`.

This is essentially the second half of [#20146](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/pull/20146). Whereas that pull request focused on providing new definitions, this one focuses on the exports and implementation style of those definitions.

The central idea behind these changes is to model the documentation and not the actual manner in which things are implemented internally within Atom. The latter has led the definitions to force extraneous information onto its users, with that information being hidden (only available through URL links to code) within the documentation itself. Types defined for use within the API aren't broken up across multiple modules and files anymore.

This also gets rid of the usage of global namespaces within the definitions as well, with all types being available off of the module export. The idea is just to leverage TypeScript's type elision for imports, with the only classes and functions being exported by the module itself.

A few of the usability benefits are:
- Usage is consistent with other TypeScript code, with types being imported and elided instead of being conjured out of a global namespace.
- Module augmentation is consistent and works the same for every type we export.
- Users are not forced to know where every type lives in code, which is hidden information within the documentation itself.

I've tried several other approaches, but there are a lot of issues that creep up whenever you have to A.) keep module exports of underlying modules in tact and B.) enable easy module augmentation.
